
A common Go setup is:

repository → service → handler → router → app

And for multiple HTTP resources, the usual pattern is:

one handler type per resource/domain
one constructor per handler
router accepts handlers, not services
app wiring creates all dependencies in one place

Why this is the standard approach

    It gives you:

     -clear separation of concerns
     -easier testing
     -easier replacement of dependencies
     -cleaner growth as features increase

Each layer has one job:

    repository talks to DB
    service holds business logic
    handler translates HTTP to service calls
    router maps URLs to handler methods
    app wires dependencies together


Recommended folder structure
internal/
  app/
    app.go
  repository/
    user_repository.go
    department_repository.go
    apartment_repository.go
  service/
    user_service.go
    department_service.go
    apartment_service.go
  transport/http/
    handlers/
      user_handler.go
      department_handler.go
      apartment_handler.go
    routes/
      router.go
      user_routes.go
      department_routes.go
      apartment_routes.go



